BioQuery API

cywhale cyrainï¼ gmail.com

2019-07-04

Open API to get statitical results from bio-database, ODB, Institute of
Oceanography, NTU. The API is in development stage and documentation is
under construction. Updates will be continued. Now the bioquery API have
following functions

  • bioquery
  • geo2map
  • geo2wwwmap
  • txt2geojson
  • site_intersect

Open API.01

POST

keyword: bioquery site2map

API cURL url: https://bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/api/bioquery/png {jpeg, pdf, svg}

site2map can plot sites, polygons, and overaly of environmental layer.
Basically it calls geo2map API, and can be incorporated with query
criteria from BioQuery web applications in bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query

Body

formdata
config

Query crieteria downloaded from BioQuery: bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query, or a config text, json, or yaml file.

return_type âsite2mapâ

return data type, here, âsite2mapâ can return png, jpeg, svg, or pdf

legend_pos âbottomâ

Optional. Legend positon: ânoneâ (no legend) âbottomrightâ, âtopleftâ, ârightâ, âbottomâ, and so on

cURL

Example Request: bioquery
site2map

curl --location --request POST "https://bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/api/bioquery/png" \   
  --form "config=@Your_File_Path" \
  --form "return_type=\"site2map\"" \   
  --form "legend_pos=\"bottom\""

Response

{style=text-align:center}

Open API.02

POST

keyword: bioquery upload user data

API cURL url: https://bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/api/bioquery/png {jpeg, pdf, svg}

Users can upload community abundance data of species assemblages, which
can be combined with ODB data (by âconfigâ parameter). This combined
data then can be used in various statistics or plotting according to
âreturn_typeâ parameter. Data format and rules of combination see:
https://bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query/?help=user_data

Body

formdata
config

Query crieteria from bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query, or a config text, json, or yaml file.

return_type âsite2mapâ

return data type, here, âsite2mapâ can return png, jpeg, svg, or pdf

datasrc

Abundance data csv file of species assemblages. Data format see: https://bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query/?help=user_data

data_mode âcombineâ

Specify how user data combined with ODB data (from config): âindepâ, âcombineâ, âcombine_regionâ or âsiteâ. Details see:https://bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query/?help=user_data

data_id âtaxonâ

Specify the variable name in datasrc which means species identification (default: âtaxonâ)

data_val âtaxon_countâ

Specify the variable name in datasrc which means species abundance or occurrence (default: âtaxon_countâ)

data_group âpolyIDâ

Specify the grouping variable name in datasrc (default: âpolyIDâ, polygonal region ID in integer)

geopoly

Optional. Can be file specified longitude and latitude of polygonal regions with id, as format âcsv_polyâ in this example, or a character vector contains geometry text with format âlonlat_polyâ, bounding box with format âBBOXâ (see next example), or BioQuery downloaded query text file with format âbioqueryâ.

format âcsv_polyâ

Optional but needed if specify geopoly: âcsvâ (CSV file with coordinates in geopoly parameter), âcsv_polyâ (CSV wity column of polygonal ID), âbioqueryâ (Config file downloaded from BioQuery: bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query), âbboxâ (bounding box), âlonlat_polyâ (string format in geopoly parameter to specify polygonal region, such as geopoly=â(124,125,124.5,124,20,21,22,20);(120,121,122,122.5,120,19,20,22,22,19)â), âkmlâ (KML file).

grd_sel 1

Optional. Specify grid for data gridding: null (raw data), 0 (0.25-deg), 1 (0.5-deg, default), 2 (1-deg)

include_poly0 false

Optional. Enable analysis including polyID==0, i.e., also analysis those sites which are outside the given polygonal regions (default: FALSE).

cURL

Example Request: bioquery upload user data

curl --location --request POST "https://bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/api/bioquery/png" \   
  --form "config=@Your_File_Path" \
  --form "return_type=\"site2map\"" \   
  --form "datasrc=@Your_File_Path" \
  --form "data_mode=\"combine\"" \   
  --form "data_id=\"taxon\"" \   
  --form "data_val=\"taxon_count\"" \   
  --form "data_group=\"polyID\"" \   
  --form "geopoly=@Your_File_Path" \
  --form "format=\"csv_poly\"" \

Response

{style=text-align:center}

Open API.03

POST

keyword: bioquery overlay environmental layer

API cURL url: https://bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/api/bioquery/png {jpeg, pdf, svg}

Environmental (Env) factors can be specified or uploaded and used in
succeeding analysis. Specify âenvsrcâ which means various sources of env
databases compiled by ODB, and âenv_layerâ, i.e., the env factors
contained in this source. Each env-layer can be applied with spatially

https://bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query/?help=bioenv

Body

formdata
config

Query crieteria from bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query, or a config text, json, or yaml file.

return_type âsite2mapâ

return data type, here, âsite2mapâ can return png, jpeg, svg, or pdf

Environmental layer name that used in the specified âenvsrcâ. See BioQuery: bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query to find all options for env_layer.

Environmental source, either a file with longitude/latitude/(season)/env_layer, or a env database provided (or compiled) by ODB, NTU. Here ânasa_neoâ means NASA NEO env data, and we fetch SST data. See BioQuery: bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query to find all options for envsrc.

by_season true

Optional. Plot with seasonality facets, if âseasonâ in specified âenvsrcâ. (default is true)

scale_res âlargeâ

Optional. Coastline resolution: âsmallâ, âmediumâ, âlargeâ

getenv_options â{&quot;en_trans&quot;:[&quot;1&quot;], &quot;scale_fun&quot;:[&quot;log&quot;], &quot;scale_mul&quot;:[&quot;1000&quot;], &quot;en_kriging&quot;:[&quot;0&quot;]}â

Optional. Json string that specify env_layer need transformation (en_trans: 1/0) by multipling a factor (scal_mul), by functions (scale_fun: âlogâ, âsqrtâ, âexpâ,â¦), or kriging (en_kriging: 1/0). Note: kriging is time-consuming

geopoly âBBOX (110,15,130,35)â

Optional. Plot map within a bounding box

format âbboxâ

Optional but needed if specify geopoly: âcsvâ (CSV file with coordinates in geopoly parameter), âcsv_polyâ (CSV wity column of polygonal ID), âbioqueryâ (Config file downloaded from BioQuery: bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/query), âbboxâ (bounding box), âlonlat_polyâ (string format in geopoly parameter to specify polygonal region, such as geopoly=â(124,125,124.5,124,20,21,22,20);(120,121,122,122.5,120,19,20,22,22,19)â), âkmlâ (KML file).

en_poly_border false

Optional. Plot outlines of polygonal region or not.

enlarge_poly_bbox false

Optional . Enlarge plotting content to include bounding box inside.

cURL

Example Request: bioquery overlay
environmental layer

curl --location --request POST "https://bio.odb.ntu.edu.tw/api/bioquery/png" \   
  --form "return_type=\"site2map\"" \   
  --form "env_layer=\"chl\"" \   
  --form "envsrc=\"nasa_neo\"" \   
  --form "by_season=true" \   
  --form "scale_res=\"large\"" \   
  --form "getenv_options='{\\\"en_trans\\\":[\\\"1\\\"], \\\"scale_fun\\\":[\\\"log\\\"], \\\"scale_mul\\\":[\\\"1000\\\"], \\\"en_kriging\\\":[\\\"0\\\"]}'" \   
  --form "geopoly=\"BBOX (110,15,130,35)\"" \   
  --form "format=\"bbox\"" \   
  --form "en_poly_border=false" \
